

**Don't thread the token through every call site by hand if you can avoid it — it's brittle at 14 touch points.** Passing `Authorization` as a per-call header works, but it means every server-side call site must remember to read the cookie and attach it, and any new call that forgets silently regresses to this same bug. Two cleaner shapes:

- **A per-request client created in request scope.** Instead of one module-level singleton, expose a small factory that reads the token via the request context and returns an instance with `Authorization` already set. Server code calls the factory (in scope), gets a ready client. This centralizes the token logic in one place while keeping it request-bound — no per-call threading, no singleton reaching for context it lacks.
- **If you keep per-call headers,** make the service function *require* the token argument (not optional), so a missing token is a type error at compile time rather than a silent 400 at runtime. That turns "someone forgot" into a build failure.

**Also split the base URL while you're in this file.** The instance uses one base URL for both server and client. Server-side calls should target the in-cluster service directly; only the browser needs the public host. Resolving the base URL by execution context (server vs client) in that same factory removes the hairpin and lets you drop the TLS-verification workaround later.

So the corrected, still-generic recommendation:

1. Server Component reads the token where request context exists. ✓ (as proposed)
2. Pass the token into the data layer **explicitly** — ideally via a **request-scoped client factory**, not hand-threaded headers on every call.
3. Make the token a **required** parameter so omissions fail at build time, not at runtime.
4. The shared interceptor no longer reads request state at all.
5. Resolve the base URL by server-vs-client in the same place, so server calls go in-cluster and you can remove the TLS workaround.

The plan on screen will work as-is; points 2–3 and 5 just make it durable so you don't re-debug this the next time someone adds an endpoint.
